The paper deals with the problem of recovering surface geometry from a single RGB image, which is a common problem in computer vision and graphics. The use of photometric stereo and the assumption of spatially-varying albedo suggest that the paper is likely to be in the computer vision (cs.CV) or graphics (cs.GR) sub-categories. The use of algorithms and theoretical analysis suggests that the paper may also be relevant to computational geometry (cs.CG) and machine learning (cs.MM). Finally, the use of a restricted number of distinct albedo values suggests that the paper may also be relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
